President Trump and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu met in the Oval Office to reaffirm the strong relationship between the United States and Israel. They discussed various issues, including countering threats from Iran and radical Islamic terrorist groups, as well as the crisis in Syria. Both leaders agreed that the Iran nuclear deal is a bad deal and emphasized that Iran should not be allowed to obtain nuclear weapons. They also talked about the Israeli-Palestinian conflict and the need for direct negotiations between the two parties for peace. The leaders agreed to form joint working groups to improve bilateral relations in areas such as cyber, intelligence, security, trade, and technology. They also expressed the desire to promote Arab-Israeli cooperation and support the growth of the Palestinian economy.